# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: shopping-cart-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] The following is a comparison of the features of notable shopping cart software packages available.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Some such shopping cart software is extensible through third-party software components and applications.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] As such, the features listed below may not encompass all possible features for a given software package.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] The software listed here is but a fraction of all such packages on the market.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Basic information about the shopping carts including creator, software license and framework, and updates.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Systems listed on a light purple background are no longer in active development.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Information about the features the shopping carts offer.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Information about which payment gateways are supported.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Information about which alternative checkouts are supported.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Information about if shopping carts have real-time shipping calculation built-in to allow calculating how much it will cost to ship an order in real time when the customer checks out an order.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Information about if shopping carts have shipment booking integration to allow staff to be able to book shipments for a number of orders at once via the control panel.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/comparison-of-shopping-cart-software] Information about if shopping carts have shipment tracking integration to show the customers the tracking information on the "View order" pages.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] A session is established at a certain point in time, and then ‘torn down’ - brought to an end - at some later point.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] An established communication session may involve more than one message in each direction.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] An established session is the basic requirement to perform a connection-oriented communication.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] A session also is the basic step to transmit in connectionless communication modes.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] However, any unidirectional transmission does not define a session.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] In the case of transport protocols that do not implement a formal session layer (e.g., UDP) or where sessions at the application layer are generally very short-lived (e.g., HTTP), sessions are maintained by a higher level program using a method defined in the data being exchanged.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] For example, an HTTP exchange between a browser and a remote host may include an HTTP cookie which identifies state, such as a unique session ID, information about the user's preferences or authorization level.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] HTTP/1.0 was thought to only allow a single request and response during one Web/HTTP Session.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Protocol version HTTP/1.1 improved this by completing the Common Gateway Interface (CGI), making it easier to maintain the Web Session and supporting HTTP cookies and file uploads.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Most client-server sessions are maintained by the transport layer - a single connection for a single session.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] However each transaction phase of a Web/HTTP session creates a separate connection.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Maintaining session continuity between phases requires a session ID.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The session ID is embedded within the `<A HREF>` or `<FORM>` links of dynamic web pages so that it is passed back to the CGI.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] CGI then uses the session ID to ensure session continuity between transaction phases.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] One advantage of one connection-per-phase is that it works well over low bandwidth (modem) connections.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] TCP sessions are typically implemented in software using child processes and/or multithreading, where a new process or thread is created when the computer establishes or joins a session.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] HTTP sessions are typically not implemented using one thread per session, but by means of a database with information about the state of each session.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The advantage with multiple processes or threads is relaxed complexity of the software, since each thread is an instance with its own history and encapsulated variables.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The disadvantage is large overhead in terms of system resources, and that the session may be interrupted if the system is restarted.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] When a client may connect to any server in a cluster of servers, a special problem is encountered in maintaining consistency when the servers must maintain session state.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The client must either be directed to the same server for the duration of the session, or the servers must transmit server-side session information via a shared file system or database.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Otherwise, the client may reconnect to a different server than the one it started the session with, which will cause problems when the new server does not have access to the stored state of the old one.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Server-side sessions are handy and efficient, but can become difficult to handle in conjunction with load-balancing/high-availability systems and are not usable at all in some embedded systems with no storage.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The load-balancing problem can be solved by using shared storage or by applying forced peering between each client and a single server in the cluster, although this can compromise system efficiency and load distribution.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] A method of using server-side sessions in systems without mass-storage is to reserve a portion of RAM for storage of session data.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] This method is applicable for servers with a limited number of clients (e.g. router or access point with infrequent or disallowed access to more than one client at a time).
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Client-side sessions use cookies and cryptographic techniques to maintain state without storing as much data on the server.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] When presenting a dynamic web page, the server sends the current state data to the client (web browser) in the form of a cookie.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The client saves the cookie in memory or on disk.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] With each successive request, the client sends the cookie back to the server, and the server uses the data to "remember" the state of the application for that specific client and generate an appropriate response.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] This mechanism may work well in some contexts; however, data stored on the client is vulnerable to tampering by the user or by software that has access to the client computer.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Data integrity: Nothing apart from the server should manipulate session data (accidentally or maliciously).
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Authenticity: Nothing apart from the server should be able to initiate valid sessions.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] To accomplish this, the server needs to encrypt the session data before sending it to the client, and modification of such information by any other party should be prevented via cryptographic means.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Transmitting state back and forth with every request is only practical when the size of the cookie is small.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] In essence, client-side sessions trade server disk space for the extra bandwidth that each web request will require.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Moreover, web browsers limit the number and size of cookies that may be stored by a web site.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] To improve efficiency and allow for more session data, the server may compress the data before creating the cookie, decompressing it later when the cookie is returned by the client.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] A session token is a unique identifier that is generated and sent from a server to a client to identify the current interaction session.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The client usually stores and sends the token as an HTTP cookie and/or sends it as a parameter in GET or POST queries.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The reason to use session tokens is that the client only has to handle the identifier—all session data is stored on the server (usually in a database, to which the client does not have direct access) linked to that identifier.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Examples of the names that some programming languages use when naming their HTTP cookie include JSESSIONID (JSP), PHPSESSID (PHP), CGISESSID (CGI), and ASPSESSIONID (ASP).
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] In human–computer interaction, **session management** is the process of keeping track of a user's activity across sessions of interaction with the computer system.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Typical session management tasks in a desktop environment include keeping track of which applications are open and which documents each application has opened, so that the same state can be restored when the user logs out and logs in later.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] For a website, session management might involve requiring the user to re-login if the session has expired (i.e., a certain time limit has passed without user activity).
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] It is also used to store information on the server-side between HTTP requests.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] A desktop session manager is a program that can save and restore desktop sessions.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] A desktop session is all the windows currently running and their current content.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Session management on Linux-based systems is provided by X session manager.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] On Microsoft Windows systems, session management is provided by the Session Manager Subsystem (smss.exe); user session functionality can be extended by third-party applications like twinsplay.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Session management is particularly useful in a web browser where a user can save all open pages and settings and restore them at a later date or on a different computer (see data portability).
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] To help recover from a system or application crash, pages and settings can also be restored on next run.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Internet Explorer, OmniWeb and Opera are examples of web browsers that support session management.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Session management is often managed through the application of cookies.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) is stateless.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Session management is the technique used by the web developer to make the stateless HTTP protocol support session state.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] For example, once a user has been authenticated to the web server, the user's next HTTP request (GET or POST) should not cause the web server to ask for the user's account and password again.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] In situations where multiple web servers must share knowledge of session state (as is typical in a cluster environment) session information must be shared between the cluster nodes that are running web server software.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] However, if session information is subject to audit compliance, consideration should be given to the method used for session storage, replication, and clustering.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] In a service-oriented architecture, Simple Object Access Protocol or SOAP messages constructed with Extensible Markup Language (XML) messages can be used by consumer applications to cause web servers to create sessions.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Just as HTTP is a stateless protocol, so is SMS.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] As SMS became interoperable across rival networks in 1999, and text messaging started its ascent towards becoming a ubiquitous global form of communication, various enterprises became interested in using the SMS channel for commercial purposes.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Initial services did not require session management since they were only one-way communications (for example, in 2000, the first mobile news service was delivered via SMS in Finland).
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] Today, these applications are referred to as application-to-peer (A2P) messaging as distinct from peer-to-peer (P2P) messaging.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/session-computer-science] The development of interactive enterprise applications required session management, but because SMS is a stateless protocol as defined by the GSM standards, early implementations were controlled client-side by having the end-users enter commands and service identifiers manually.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] The software allows online shopping customers to accumulate a list of items for purchase.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] At the point of sale, the software typically calculates a total for the order, including freight transport, postage as well as packaging and labeling.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Associated taxes are calculated as applicable.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] This software also allows for a final review of the shortlisted purchase and the choice for a user to modify the purchase.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] The data is used in online marketing particularly in the form of abandoned carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] The development of web shop systems took place right after the Internet became a mass medium.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] This was a result of the launch of the browser Mosaic in 1993 and Netscape in 1994.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] It created an environment in which web shops were possible.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] The Internet therefore acted as the key infrastructure development that contributed to the rapid diffusion of the e-commerce, a subset of e-business that describes all computer-aided business transactions.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] In 1998 a total of 11 e-business models were observed, one of which was e-shop business model for a B2C (business-to-consumer) business—also called the “online shop” The two terms “online shop” and “electronic” or “e-shop” are used interchangeably.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] The term “online shopping” was invented much earlier in 1984.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Today the term primarily refers to the business-to-consumer transactional business.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] In order to enable “online shopping” a software system is needed.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Since “online shopping”, in the context of the B2C business model, became broadly available to the end consumer, internet-based “online shops” evolved.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] These applications typically provide a means of capturing a client's payment information, but in the case of a credit card they rely on the software module of the secure gateway provider, in conjunction with the secure payment gateway, in order to conduct secure credit card transactions online.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Some setup must be done in the HTML code of the website, and the shopping cart software must be installed on the server which hosts the site, or on the server which accepts sensitive ordering information.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] E-shopping carts are usually implemented using HTTP cookies or query strings.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] In most server based implementations however, data related to the shopping cart is kept in the session object and is accessed and manipulated on the fly, as the user selects different items from the cart.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Later in the process of finalizing the transaction, the information is accessed and an order is generated against the selected item thus clearing the shopping cart.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Although the most simple shopping carts strictly allow for an item to be added to a basket to start a checkout process (e.g., the free PayPal shopping cart), most shopping cart software provides additional features that an Internet merchant uses to fully manage an online store.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Data (products, categories, discounts, orders, customers, etc.) is normally stored in a database and accessed in real time by the software.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Shopping cart software is also known as e-commerce software, e-store software, online store software or storefront software and online shop.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] The PCI security standards are a blanket of regulations set in place to safeguard payment account data security.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] The council that develops and monitors these regulations is composed of the leading providers in the payment industry: American Express, Discover Financial Services, JCB International, Mastercard, and Visa Inc.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Essentially, they define the best practices for storing, transmitting, and handling of sensitive information over the internet.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] Visa Inc. can hold shopping cart software providers responsible for liability that may occur as a result of non-compliance to Visa's regulations.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart-software] For this reason, Visa Inc. may require that online merchants use shopping cart software providers from their list of PCI DSS-validated service providers.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Most modern shopping carts are made of metal or a combination of metal and plastic and have been designed to nest within each other in a line to facilitate collecting and moving many at one time and also to save on storage space.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The carts can come in many sizes, with larger ones able to carry a child.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] There are also specialized carts designed for two children, and electric mobility scooters with baskets designed for individuals with disabilities.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] As of 2006, approximately 24,000 children are injured in the United States each year in shopping carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Some stores both in the U.S. and internationally have child carrying carts that look like a car or van with a seat where a child can sit equipped with a steering wheel and sometimes a horn.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Such "Car-Carts" may offer protection and convenience by keeping the child restrained, lower to the ground, protected from falling items, and amused.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Shopping carts are usually fitted with four wheels, however if any one wheel jams the cart can become difficult to handle.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Most carts in the United States have swivel wheels at the front, while the rear wheels are fixed in orientation, while in Europe it is more common to have four swivel wheels.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] This difference in design correlates with smaller retail premises in Europe.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The front part of the cart is often sectioned off in order to place household goods such as bleach, cleaning products etc. so that they do not mix with edible products.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] An alternative to the shopping cart is a small hand-held shopping basket.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] A customer may prefer a basket for a small amount of merchandise.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Small shops, where carts would be impractical, often supply only baskets, or may offer a small cart which uses an inserted shopping basket within the frame of the cart to provide either choice to a customer.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] One of the first shopping carts was introduced on June 4, 1937, the invention of Sylvan Goldman, owner of the Humpty Dumpty supermarket chain in Oklahoma.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] One night, in 1936, Goldman sat in his office wondering how customers might move more groceries.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] He found a wooden folding chair and put a basket on the seat and wheels on the legs.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Goldman and one of his employees, a mechanic named Fred Young, began tinkering.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Their first shopping cart was a metal frame that held two wire baskets.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Since they were inspired by the folding chair, Goldman called his carts "folding basket carriers".
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Another mechanic, Arthur Kosted, developed a method to mass-produce the carts by inventing an assembly line capable of forming and welding the wire.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The cart was awarded patent number 2,196,914 on April 9, 1940 (Filing date: March 14, 1938), titled, "Folding Basket Carriage for Self-Service Stores".
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] They advertised the invention as part of a new "No Basket Carrying Plan".
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Goldman had already pioneered self-serve stores and carts were part of the self-serve retail concept.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The invention did not catch on immediately.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Men found them effeminate; women found them suggestive of a baby carriage.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] "I've pushed my last baby," an offended woman informed Goldman.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] After Goldman hired several male and female models to push his new invention around his store and demonstrate their utility, as well as greeters to explain their use, shopping carts became extremely popular and Goldman became a multimillionaire.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In urban areas like New York City, where transporting groceries home from the store's parking lot is more likely to involve walking and/or a trip by public transportation than a car ride, privately owned carts resembling Goldman's design are still popular.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Instead of baskets, these carts are built to hold the paper bags dispensed by the grocery store.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Another shopping cart innovator was Orla Watson, who invented the swinging rear door to allow for "nesting" in 1946.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Orla Watson continued to make modifications to his original design.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Advice from his trusted business partners Fred Taylor, a grocery store owner in Kansas City, and George O'Donnell, a grocery store refrigeration salesman, and the incorporation of Watson's swinging door yielded the familiar nesting cart that we see today using the "double-decker" approach.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Goldman patented a similar version of the cart with only one basket rather than the double-decker feature, which he called the "Nest-Kart" in 1948, over one year after Watson filed for his patent.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The Nest-Kart incorporated the same nesting mechanism present on the shopping carts designed by Watson, and an interference investigation was ordered by Telescope Carts, Inc. alleging infringement of the patent in 1948.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] After a protracted legal battle, Goldman ultimately recognized Watson's invention and paid one dollar in damages for counterfeit, in exchange for which Watson granted Goldman an exclusive operating license (apart from the three licenses that had already been granted).
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In 1909, Bessie DeCamp invented a seat belt for chairs, go-carts or carriages.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] This was well before shopping carts with child seating areas were invented.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Goldman introduced a child seating area on shopping carts in 1947.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] For whatever reason, it wasn't until 1967 that seat belts for shopping carts were introduced by David Allen.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] It was high tech for the time, because it was a retractable seat belt.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In 1946, Orla Watson devised a system for a telescoping (i.e., "nesting") shopping cart which did not require assembly or disassembly of its parts before and after use like Goldman's cart; Goldman's design up until this point required that the cart be unfolded much like a folding chair.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] This cart could be fitted into another cart for compact storage via a swinging one-way rear door.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The swinging rear door formed the basis of the patent claim, and was a major innovation in the evolution of the modern shopping cart.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Watson applied for a patent on his shopping cart invention in 1946, but Goldman contested it and filed an application for a similar patent with the swinging door feature on a shopping cart with only one basket in 1948 which Goldman named the "Nest-Kart".
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] After considerable litigation and allegations of patent infringement, Goldman relinquished his rights to the patent in 1949 to Watson and his company, Telescope Carts, Inc. realizing that the swinging rear door feature was the key to Watson's patent.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In exchange, Goldman was granted an exclusive licensing right in addition to the three other licenses previously granted; Telescope Carts, Inc. continued to receive royalties for each cart produced by Goldman's company that incorporated the "nesting" design.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] This included any shopping cart utilizing his hinged rear door, including the familiar single basket "nesting" designs similar to those used in the present.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Owing to its overwhelming success, many different manufacturers desired to produce shopping carts with the rear swinging door feature but were denied due to the exclusive license issued to Goldman.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The federal government filed a lawsuit against Telescope Carts, Inc. in 1950 alleging the exclusive license granted to Goldman was invalid, and a Consent Decree was entered into where Telescope Carts, Inc. agreed to offer the same license to any manufacturer.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Orla Watson and Telescope Carts, Inc. licensed their telescoping shopping cart design to several manufacturers throughout the 1950s and 1960s until the patent expired.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In 2012, a driverless shopping cart was made by Chaotic Moon Labs.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The device, called "Project Sk8" or "Smarter Cart" was basically a cart fitted with Windows Kinect (to detect obstacles), and an electric drivetrain, and used in conjunction with a Windows 8 tablet.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] For smaller stores, shopping baskets with wheels can be used either as a large basket or a small cart.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] These carts are designed for indoor use only.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In 2017, a mobile device shelf was added to shopping carts at Target stores to support the digital in-store shopping experience.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The shelf was invented and designed by Nick Dyer, a former employee of Target.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The introduction of "EASY Shopper" in 2019 by Pentland Firth Software GmbH in partnership with the German retailer EDEKA represents another step in the evolution of shopping carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Equipped with a tablet, barcode scanner, and cashierless checkout system, the smart shopping cart aims to provide customers with a more streamlined and convenient shopping experience.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The system utilizes computer vision to accurately track items in the cart and allow customers to scan and pay for their purchases as they shop, reducing the need to stand in line and wait to pay for their items.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Past studies determined that retailers who did not offer shopping carts such as Sears suffered lower sales in comparison to retailers who did use shopping carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Subsequent to the introduction of shopping carts and centralized checkout lines at Sears stores, the company noticed a correlating increase in sales.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In 2004, British supermarket chain Tesco trialed shopping carts with user-adjustable wheel resistance, heart rate monitoring and calorie counting hardware in an effort to raise awareness of health issues.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The cart's introduction coincided with Tesco's sponsorship of Cancer Research UK's fundraising event Race for Life.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Also in 2004, shopping carts were identified as a source of pathogens and became a major public health concern.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] This was primarily due to the media spotlight on a Japanese research study revealing large amounts of bacteria on shopping carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Those findings were later backed by a University of Arizona study in 2007.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In 2009, researchers developed prototypes of computerized context aware shopping carts by attaching tablet computers to ordinary carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Initial field trials showed that the prototype's context awareness provided an opportunity for enhancing and altering the shopping experience.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Some retailers, such as Target, have begun using carts fully made of recycled plastic with the only metal part being the wheel axles, drawing away from the established metal cart design.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Target's cart has won design awards for its improved casters, interchangeable plastic parts to simplify repairs, and handles that improve maneuverability.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Smaller half-sized carts for smaller shopping trips have also become common.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In many countries, the customer has to make a small deposit by inserting a coin, token or card, which is returned if and when the customer returns the cart to a designated cart parking point.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The system works through a lock mounted on the handle of the cart, connecting it to a chain mounted on the cart in front of it when nested together, or to a chain mounted on a cart collection corral.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Inserting the token unlocks the chain, and reinserting the chain locks it in place and ejects the token for user to retrieve.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] One motivation behind the deposit system is to reduce the expense of employees having to gather carts that are not returned, and to avoid damage done by runaway carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Another benefit is that carts are less likely to be removed from the store premises and abandoned in the surrounding neighborhood.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Carts that are not returned may be returned voluntarily by a pedestrian, with the deposit coin acting as a reward.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Although almost ubiquitous in continental Europe and the UK, the deposit system is less common in Canada and has not been widely adopted in the United States, with the exception of some chains like ALDI, which require a $0.25 deposit.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] One of the first store chains to use the $0.25 deposit system in the US was the Real Superstore (a subsidiary of National Supermarkets) in the early 1990s.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Other stores such as Costco and ShopRite also use the coin deposit system, but it is not used at all of their locations.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In Australia, deposit systems are common in some local government areas, as they have been made compulsory by local law.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Usually, all ALDI stores, and most Coles and Woolworths stores will have a lock mechanism on their carts that requires a $1 or $2 coin to unlock.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The deposit varies, but usually coins of higher value, such as €1, £1, or $1 are used.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] While the deposit systems usually are designed to accommodate a certain size of domestic coin, foreign coins, former currencies (like German D-Marks), or even appropriately folded pieces of cardboard can be used to unlock the carts as well.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Cart collectors are also usually provided with a special key that they can use to unlock the carts from the cart bay and get the key back.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Some retailers sell "tokens" as an alternative to coins, often for charity.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Merchandising companies also offer branded shopping tokens as a product.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Shopping cart theft can be a costly problem with stores that use them.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The carts, which typically cost between $75 and $150 each, with some models costing $300–400, are removed by people for various purposes.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] To prevent theft, estimated at $800 million worldwide per annum, stores use various security systems as discussed below.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Most retailers in North America utilize a cart retrieval service, which collects carts found off the store's premises and returns them to the store for a fee.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The primary strength of this system is the ability of pedestrian customers to take purchases home and allow retailers to recapture abandoned carts in a timely manner at a fraction of the cost of a replacement cart.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] It also allows retailers to maintain their cart inventories without an expensive capital outlay.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] A drawback of this method is that it is reactive, instead of proactively preventing the carts from leaving the store premises.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Electronic systems are sometimes used by retailers.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Each shopping cart is fitted with an electronic locking wheel clamp, or "boot".
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] A transmitter with a thin wire is placed around the perimeter of the parking lot, and the boot locks when the cart leaves the designated area.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Store personnel must then deactivate the lock with a handheld remote control to return the cart to stock.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Often, a line is painted in front of the broadcast range to warn customers that their cart will stop when rolled past the line.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] However, these systems are very expensive to install and although helpful, are not foolproof.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The wheels can be lifted over the electronic barrier and/or pushed hard enough that the locks break.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] There are also safety concerns if the person pushing the trolley is running, and also if the trolley doesn't lock and is taken onto a road, locking due to magnetic materials under the road.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Some cities have required retailers to install locking wheel systems on their shopping carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In some cases, electronic systems companies have encouraged passage of such laws to create a captive audience of potential customers.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] A low-tech form of theft prevention utilizes a physical impediment, such as vertical posts at the store entrance to keep carts from being taken into the parking lot.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] This method also impedes physically disabled customers, which may be illegal in many jurisdictions.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] For example, in the United States it would be a violation of the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Another method (used for example by UK supermarket Iceland) is to mount a pole taller than the entrance, onto the shopping cart, so that the pole will block exit of the cart.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] However, this method requires that the store aisles be higher than the pole, including lights, piping, any overhead signage and fixtures.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] It also prevents customers from carting their purchases to their cars in the store's carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Many customers learn to bring their own folding or otherwise collapsible cart with them, which they can usually hang on the store's cart while shopping.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] A further system is to use a cattle grid style system.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] All pedestrian exits have specially designed flooring tiles, which, along with specially designed wheels on the cart, will immobilize the cart as they roll onto them.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Like the magnetic systems, this can easily be overcome by lifting the cart over the tiles.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The names of shopping carts vary by region.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] The following names are region-specific names for shopping carts.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Special electronic shopping carts are provided by many retailers for the elderly or disabled people.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] These are essentially electric wheelchairs with an attached basket.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] They allow customers to navigate around the store and collect items.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Manually powered carts are also available specifically designed for use by wheelchair users.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] A still-to-be-implemented aid for people with disabilities is the addition of a guide wheel at the center of rotation of a cart with four caster wheels.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In order to allow the nesting of carts to be unhindered, this guide wheel is attached to the front of the cart with a piece of spring steel which bends under the cart's weight.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Caroline's Carts are designed for aiding non-ambulatory adults or larger children, but require an additional person to push.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Olivier Mourgue, Otl Aicher, *Stiletto* as well as other artists and designers had wire furniture or artwork made by shopping cart manufacturers.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] One of the most famous thematizations of a shopping cart in art is the 1970 sculpture "Supermarket Lady" by US pop artist Duane Hanson, which is critical of consumerism.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] In 1983, the neoist "one-man artist group" *Stiletto Studios*, from Berlin converted a 'stray' shopping cart into an 'inverted' *cantilever*-wire chair on the principle of *objet trouvé*.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] Another example is found in Massurrealism, a grass-roots genre started in 1992.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] This art movement merges surrealism with mass media, and was inspired by the use of the shopping cart to comment on contemporary society's mass media saturation and consumer-driven culture.
[src:shopping-cart-systems/shopping-cart] By far, most stolen shopping carts that are not returned and left outside their location, however, are misappropriated by occasional subsequent and secondary users without any artistic or cultural-critical readymade intentions as emergency solutions.
